# JavaScript Conventions

## No innerHTML for user data — always use DOM APIs

```js
// ❌ BAD — XSS risk
el.innerHTML = `<a href="${row.url}">${row.description}</a>`;

// ✅ GOOD
const a = document.createElement('a');
a.href = safeHttpUrl(row.url); // validate protocol first
a.textContent = row.description;
```

## Validate URLs before setting href

```js
function safeHttpUrl(url) {
  try {
    const u = new URL(url);
    if (u.protocol === 'http:' || u.protocol === 'https:') return u.href;
  } catch {}
  return null; // render as <span>, not <a>
}
```

## Bind events in JS — no inline onclick attributes

```js
// ❌ BAD
el.innerHTML = `<button onclick="deleteItem('${id}')">Delete</button>`;

// ✅ GOOD
btn.addEventListener('click', () => deleteItem(id));
```

## Async patterns
- Use `void fn()` to fire-and-forget without suppressing lint warnings
- Always `await` IndexedDB helpers — they all return Promises
- Debounce filter input (~220 ms) to avoid re-render churn

## Module structure
Each file has one clear responsibility. Import only what is needed.
Never import `main.js` from other modules — it is the leaf entry point.

## Tests
Run with: `node --test js/url-utils.test.js js/rtf.test.js`
Add tests for any new parsing or grouping logic in `url-utils.js`.
